5. Product modules

Module 1: Ambient Documentation Engine

The scribe layer.

Functions:
	•	voice-to-structured charting
	•	carry-forward with change detection
	•	auto-link events to documentation destinations
	•	generate narrative notes from structured state
	•	de-duplicate repeated data entry

Example

From:
	•	med scan
	•	pain score
	•	reassessment timer
	•	nurse voice memo

It drafts:
	•	administration note
	•	pain intervention entry
	•	follow-up reminder
	•	reassessment documentation shell

⸻

Module 2: Clinical Memory Graph

The heart of the system.

This is not just a note buffer.
It is a patient-specific temporal graph of:
	•	observations
	•	actions
	•	responses
	•	changes
	•	pending loops

Why this matters

Normal EHRs store fragments.
Nightingale stores state transitions.

Not:

“BP 146/88”

But:

“BP rose across three readings after pain increase and before PRN administration, then improved.”

That is actual clinical memory.

⸻

Module 3: Chart Gap Sentinel

This is the legal and operational shield.

It detects:
	•	required reassessments not completed
	•	intervention documented without response
	•	restraint/fall bundle gaps
	•	sepsis screening timing gaps
	•	wound charting inconsistencies
	•	pain med follow-up missing
	•	overdue line/drain documentation

The tone must be:
	•	specific
	•	quiet
	•	evidence-linked
	•	impossible to mistake for autonomous authority

Example:
“Pain reassessment likely due. Oxycodone charted 42 min ago; no follow-up pain response documented.”

⸻

Module 4: Handoff Intelligence

This solves one of the most painful problems in nursing.

A handoff needs:
	•	state
	•	change
	•	danger
	•	pending
	•	behavior/context

Nightingale should auto-compose this.

Example

State: Alert, on 2L NC, pain controlled.
Change: Required 4L during ambulation; now back to 2L.
Risk: Fall risk increased; more impulsive this afternoon.
Pending: Evening labs, wound consult, monitor O2 with activity.
Context: Responds better to calm stepwise explanation; daughter updates reduce anxiety.

That last line is gold. The chart rarely protects it. Nurses carry it in their heads.

⸻

Module 5: Risk Sentinel

Not diagnosis. Not replacement judgment.
Pattern vigilance.

Signals:
	•	respiratory decline
	•	sepsis trajectory
	•	delirium drift
	•	pressure injury buildup
	•	falls probability shift
	•	fluid imbalance
	•	med timing hazards

Each flag must contain:
	•	pattern summary
	•	evidence
	•	confidence
	•	suggested nurse action category

Example:
“Possible early respiratory decline: RR trend up, oxygen need increased with activity, new diminished bases note. Consider bedside reassessment.”

⸻

Module 6: Nurse Operations Assistant

This is where the bigger wedge lives.

Functions:
	•	bundle tasks by room and urgency
	•	surface likely forgotten loops
	•	prioritize by patient instability + due times
	•	show interruption cost
	•	prep a nurse’s next 30 minutes
	•	support charge nurse load-balancing

This becomes the attention router for the unit.

