9. UX principles

Principle 1: Chat is not the main interface

A chatbot alone is wrong for this problem.

Nurses need:
	•	cards
	•	toggles
	•	glanceable timelines
	•	one-tap approvals
	•	mobile-first speed

Chat can exist as a sidecar, not the cockpit.

Principle 2: Exception-first

For stable patients, the system should ask:
“What changed?”
not:
“Re-document everything.”

Principle 3: Every click must collapse more future work

No dead clicks.

Principle 4: Confidence must be visible

People trust what they can inspect.

Principle 5: Silence is a feature

The best system does not chatter. It waits until useful.

⸻

10. Safety and governance

Absolute rules

Nightingale must never:
	•	fabricate care
	•	sign documentation
	•	invent assessments
	•	alter historical timestamps silently
	•	place orders
	•	diagnose autonomously
	•	hide uncertainty
	•	overwrite nurse edits

Required controls
	•	full audit log
	•	user-level provenance
	•	suggestion acceptance/rejection tracking
	•	source evidence access
	•	policy engine for what can auto-draft
	•	rollback and redline history
	•	PHI boundary enforcement

Confidence tiers
	•	Tier 1: direct machine capture
	•	Tier 2: direct nurse voice capture
	•	Tier 3: structured inference from multiple sources
	•	Tier 4: weak suggestion only, explicit confirmation required

